Additional exercises

Prove the four logical equivalences and give concrete examples of the two non-equivalences on the last slide for 1.4 "Predicate and Quantifiers".

For the first four ones, try to convince yourself why they are true. Understand when the left-hand side is true, and when it is false. Do the same for the right-hand side. Do they always have the same truth value? If yes, then they are equivalent.

For the last two ones, try to construct counter examples. There are many possible ways to do this.

For the first of them, you could for example choose P(x)P(x)P(x)P(x) to be any statement about xxxx such that for at least one yyyy, P(y)P(y)P(y)P(y) is true, and then let Q(x)=\neg P(x)Q(x)=¬P(x)Q(x)=\neg P(x)Q(x)=¬P(x).

For the last of the two, notice that the left-hand side implies the right-hand side. So you will have to come up with a counter example that satisfy the right-hand side, but not the left-hand side. That is, there should not exist any element xxxx that makes both P(x)P(x)P(x)P(x) and Q(x)Q(x)Q(x)Q(x) true. But there should be (at least) two elements y\neq zy≠zy\neq zy=z such that P(y)P(y)P(y)P(y) and P(z)P(z)P(z)P(z) are true.

  1. The statement \neg\forall x P(x)¬∀xP(x)\neg\forall x P(x)¬∀xP(x) is true if and only if it is not the case that all xxxx makes P(x)P(x)P(x)P(x) true. In other words, there exists (at leaste one) xxxx such that P(x)P(x)P(x)P(x) is false, i.e., \neg P(x)¬P(x)\neg P(x)¬P(x) is true. Symbolically, we can write this as \exists x \neg P(x)∃x¬P(x)\exists x \neg P(x)∃x¬P(x).
  2. The statement \neg\exists P(x)¬∃P(x)\neg\exists P(x)¬∃P(x) means that it is not the case that there exists some xxxx making P(x)P(x)P(x)P(x) true. In other words, P(x)P(x)P(x)P(x) is false for all xxxx, which we can write as \forall x \neg P(x)∀x¬P(x)\forall x \neg P(x)∀x¬P(x).
  3. For all xxxx, both P(x)P(x)P(x)P(x) and Q(x)Q(x)Q(x)Q(x) are true. In other words, all xxxx makes P(x)P(x)P(x)P(x) true and all xxxx makes Q(x)Q(x)Q(x)Q(x) true. Symbolically that is \forall x P(x)\wedge\forall x Q(x)∀xP(x)∧∀xQ(x)\forall x P(x)\wedge\forall x Q(x)∀xP(x)∧∀xQ(x).
  4. There exists at least one xxxx that makes P(x)\vee Q(x)P(x)∨Q(x)P(x)\vee Q(x)P(x)∨Q(x) true. If xxxx makes P(x)P(x)P(x)P(x) true, then \exists x P(x)∃xP(x)\exists x P(x)∃xP(x) is true (and similarly for Q(x)Q(x)Q(x)Q(x)). In other words, the LHS implies the RHS. The other direction in similar.
  5. Example: Let x range over all integers. Let P(x) : "x is an even number" and let $Q(x) : "x is an odd number". Then the left-hand side \forall x (P(x)\vee Q(x))∀x(P(x)∨Q(x))\forall x (P(x)\vee Q(x))∀x(P(x)∨Q(x)) is true because every integer is either odd or even. The right-hand side however is not true as it translates into "all integers are even OR all integers are odd" neither of which is true.
  6. Example: Let P(x) and Q(x) be as before. The right-hand side is true, for example, P(2) and Q(3) are both true. But the left-hand side says that there exists some integer xxxx which is both even and odd which we know is impossible.
